[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering dynamic access**\n\nI'm thinking about how the dynamic-access report might work. It seems agent instruments could be loaded by class name, no matter the classloader. If a custom loader loads the Ant jar, the agent might still see dynamic access, but I wonder if JaCoCo would behave differently.\n\nHmm, perhaps it’s easier to use ClassLoader.getSystemResource to locate ClassConstants.class. I need to make sure it's loaded from the same instrumented classpath; that’s crucial for the task.\n\n**Evaluating runtime class path in Gradle**\n\nI’m exploring how to set the `java.class.path` runtime in `build.gradle`. It seems like adding `runtimeArgs(\"-Djava.class.path=${sourceSets.test.runtimeClasspath.asPath}\")` is a potential solution, but there’s concern about native executables not being able to load classes from jars due to unsupported features. To address this, I think I need to add a second test that catches the `Error`, particularly for JVM agent compatibility. I’ll also need to check unsupported feature errors specifically and may consider using `ChainReaderHelper` for reflection instead.\n\n**Exploring classpath setup with AntClassLoader**\n\nI’m considering using `AntClassLoader` because `ChainReaderHelper` doesn’t expose necessary details. I need to find the classpath path in my Java test. First, I plan to create a `Project` object, then set up a `Path` using `System.getProperty(\"java.class.path\")`, which could include class directories and jars. For constructing the `AntClassLoader`, I’m debating whether to set the parent to the system class loader or leave it as null. This setup seems promising for what I need!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f1153feb7ac16c80169f55c494c8081a3add49b0bb2fe96db\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9Vx4Df2nCt_-S0FdrzrhJS6y7ZPzwvN6KOdNW8_vSyu-4naOGzeIhqVTJ9n8ID1A2Ofx_SyjhTnJXo9j6ZlquM